# 🔹 ε-NFA (Epsilon-NFA)

An **ε-NFA** is an NFA that allows **ε-transitions**.

An ε-transition allows the automaton to move from one state to another **without consuming any input symbol**.

Example:

```text
q0 --ε--> q1
```

The automaton changes state without reading the input.

---

# 🔹 ε-Closure

### Definition

The **ε-closure** of a state is the set of all states reachable using **zero or more ε-transitions**.

---

### Example

```text
q0 --ε--> q1 --ε--> q2
```

Then:

[
\varepsilon\text{-closure}(q_0)={q_0,q_1,q_2}
]

📌 Computing ε-closure is essential when converting an ε-NFA to a DFA.

---

# 🔹 NFA to DFA Conversion (Subset Construction)

Every NFA has an equivalent DFA.

The standard conversion technique is called the **Subset Construction Algorithm**.

---

## Steps

### Step 1

Find the start state.

For ε-NFA, compute the ε-closure of the start state.

---

### Step 2

For each input symbol, compute the set of reachable states.

---

### Step 3

Treat each **set of NFA states** as a **single DFA state**.

Example:

```text
{q0,q1}
```

becomes one DFA state.

---

### Step 4

Repeat until no new state sets are generated.

---

### Step 5

Any DFA state containing an NFA accepting state becomes an accepting DFA state.

---

# 🔹 Example

Suppose:

```text
δ(q0,a)={q0,q1}

δ(q1,a)={q2}
```

DFA States become:

```text
{q0}

{q0,q1}

{q0,q1,q2}
```

Each set acts as one DFA state.

---

# 🔹 Why Convert NFA to DFA?

Computers execute DFAs more efficiently because:

* Exactly one transition per input.
* Easier implementation.
* Used in lexical analyzers and pattern matching.

---

# 🔹 DFA vs NFA vs ε-NFA

| Feature                  | DFA               | NFA               | ε-NFA             |
| ------------------------ | ----------------- | ----------------- | ----------------- |
| One transition per input | ✅                 | ❌                 | ❌                 |
| Multiple transitions     | ❌                 | ✅                 | ✅                 |
| ε-Transitions            | ❌                 | ❌                 | ✅                 |
| Recognition Power        | Regular Languages | Regular Languages | Regular Languages |

📌 **Important:** All three recognize **exactly the same class of languages** (Regular Languages).

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

NFA is **not more powerful** than DFA.

Both recognize Regular Languages.

---

### Trap 2

An NFA accepts if **at least one computation path** reaches a final state.

---

### Trap 3

ε-transitions consume **no input**.

---

### Trap 4

The number of DFA states after conversion can be up to:

[
2^n
]

where n is the number of NFA states.

---

### Trap 5

A DFA **cannot** have ε-transitions.

---

# 📝 Formula Sheet

| Concept            | Formula / Rule                       |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------------ |
| DFA Transition     | δ : Q × Σ → Q                        |
| NFA Transition     | δ : Q × Σ → 2ᴽ                       |
| ε-Closure          | States reachable using ε-transitions |
| Maximum DFA States | 2ⁿ                                   |
| Accepted by NFA    | At least one accepting path          |

